{"key":"processedPost-12064245","value":{"id":12064245,"first":11764015,"last":12118516,"when":1266680041,"utime":"02/20/10 05:34 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>pblcenmy1 said:</strong><br />senescence deals mostly with aging after full maturity.&nbsp; You could clone a young commercial shitake and get good results.&nbsp; No need to buy a syringe for this mush, unless you question your environments sterilitity.</blockquote><br />That is incorrect.&nbsp; Senescence deals with the number of cell divisions since the two spores germinated into hyphae, and then the compatible hyphae 'mated', forming dikaryotic mycelium.<br />Cloning a store-bought shiitake is going to be hit or miss, mainly miss.&nbsp; I'm a small shiitake farmer, but I still do four to five grain to grain transfers using 5 pounds of rye berries in each spawn bag, so my mycelium is really grown out by the time it fruits.&nbsp; I'd hate to start that process over at square one again.&nbsp; If you're seriously into growing edibles, you should pony up the bux and get a good culture.&nbsp; They're $225 each at aloha medicinals, but you'll get young cell lines with aggressive growth, and proved fruiting performance. <br />RR","title":"Re: Shiitake cloning"}}